Introduction

In studies conducted outside of the United States, people who were able to commute via physical activity (such as walking and bike riding) were also significantly associated with increased health indicators (ChillÃ³n, et al., 2012; Andersen et al., 2011). Additionally, those who have access and regularly use public transportation have decreased commute stress compared to those who drive daily(link).

Although it is known in public health and urban planning literature, the majority of the United States is a car centered landscape. Starting in the 1920âs, the American population became increasingly interested in personal motor vehicles, forcing administrators and engineers to rapidly build road infrastructure without regard to future potential problems (link). In 2019, the US Census Bureau reported that 75% of Americans drive alone as their means of transportation, 5% use public transportation, and less than 3% use physical exercise (link).

In order to investigate this gap between knowledge and practice, the California Health and Human Services Open Data Portal was utilized to access transportation and health data. In the portal, I used a dataset called âTransportation to Workâ from the Healthy Communities Data and Indicators Project of the Office of Health Equity. Although the datasets provide a comprehensive overview of transportation in America, the main variable I will focus on is the frequency of different types of transportation. Health status indicators were also accessed through the California Health and Human Services Open Data portal via a report by the California Department of Public health and the California Conference of Local Health Officers entitled, âCounty Health Status Profilesâ. In the dataset, health indicators were collected at county-level. For this project, the following health indicators were utilized: Deaths Due to Alzeimerâs Disease, Deaths Due to Coronary Heart Disease, and Deaths Due to Diabetes. Additionally, the county rankings based on overall age-adjusted health indicators were utilized. In this study, multiple questions will be answered that all address the overarching question: What is the association between different health indicators (diseases) and mode of transportation? The associations that will be investigated are:

  1. Car vs.Â Alzheimerâs disease

  2. Car vs Coronary heart disease

  3. Car vs Diabetes

  4. Physical vs Alzheimerâs disease

  5. Physical vsÂ  Coronary heart disease

  6. Physical vs Diabetes

  7. Public transportation vs Alzheimerâs disease

  8. Public transportation vs Diabetes

  9. Public transportation vsÂ  Coronary heart disease

Along with the possible confounder location (County vs.Â all diseases)

Methods

The first step after reading in the data was to rename new variables, limit each data-set to counties in Southern California only in order to make resulting comparisons with as minimal differences as possible., as well as limit data-sets to a report year(s) and demographics. Further, the health indicator variable was condensed into deaths due to Alzheimer\âs disease, deaths due to coronary heart disease, and deaths due to diabetes (these health indicator variables were known to be more influenced by social determinants of health and daily activities).

healthind <-c("Deaths Due to Alzheimer's Disease","Deaths Due to Coronary Heart Disease","Deaths Due to Diabetes")
countyhealth <- filter(countyhealth, Health_Indicator_Desc %in% healthind)
countyhealth <- mutate(countyhealth, coronary= ifelse(Health_Indicator_Desc=="Deaths Due to Coronary Heart Disease",1 ,0))
countyhealth <- mutate(countyhealth, alzheimer= ifelse(Health_Indicator_Desc=="Deaths Due to Alzheimer's Disease",1 ,0))
countyhealth <- mutate(countyhealth, diabetes= ifelse(Health_Indicator_Desc=="Deaths Due to Diabetes",1 ,0))

**needed chatgpt help with code above to create new variable based on multiple conditions

countyhealth$coronaryrate <- ifelse(countyhealth$coronary == 1 & countyhealth$Health_Indicator_Desc == "Deaths Due to Coronary Heart Disease",  countyhealth$`Age-Adjusted_Rate`, NA)
countyhealth$alzheimerrate <- ifelse(countyhealth$alzheimer == 1 & countyhealth$Health_Indicator_Desc == "Deaths Due to Alzheimer's Disease",  countyhealth$`Age-Adjusted_Rate`, NA)
countyhealth$diabetesrate <- ifelse(countyhealth$diabetes == 1 & countyhealth$Health_Indicator_Desc == "Deaths Due to Diabetes",  countyhealth$`Age-Adjusted_Rate`, NA)
countyhealth = subset(countyhealth, select = -c(Annotation_Desc, Rates_Annotation_Code, Numerator_Annotation_Code, Denominator_Annotation_Code, Rate_Multiplier, Numerator_Year_Period, Numerator_Total, Numerator_Average,Denominator_Total, Table, Healthy_People_Objective_Number, Healthy_People_Objective_Met
) )
countyhealth <- filter(countyhealth, Strata=="Total Population")

After, all variables that were not going to be used were removed from each data-set in order to reduce the data-set sizes. Then, data-sets were merged based on the County variable, and the data-set was checked for duplicates. Continuing the data cleaning process, the proportion of missing values in each key variable were checked (all variables had less than 2% of NA values) and verified to continue. Implausible values were checked for each main key variable(none were found). Following this, variables with difficult or ambiguous names were renamed, and new categorical variables were created. The ranking of each county variable was made into a new variable to distinguish counties that had low, low-mid, mid, and high rankings. The mode of transportation variable was narrowed down into a simpler categorical variable (ex: bike riding and walking were combined into one âphysicalâ subcategory). .

transhealth <- merge(
  # Data
  x     = worktransport3,      
  y     = countyhealth, 
  # List of variables to match
  by.x  = "County",
  by.y  = "County", 
  # Which obs to keep?
  all.x = TRUE,      
  all.y = TRUE
  )
transhealth <- mutate(transhealth,
                      modenew = ifelse(mode == "BICYCLE" | mode == "WALK", "physical",
                                      ifelse(mode == "CAR" | mode == "CARTOTAL" | mode == "CARPOOL", "car",
                                             ifelse(mode == "PUBLICTR", "publictr", "athome"))))

**used chatgpt above to correct code (original code ex: mode == âBICYCLEâ|âWALKâ)

transhealth <- mutate (transhealth, rankcat = ifelse(Rank_Order >25, "low", "high"))

Preliminary Results

Summary statistics tables did not show any differences across different transportation methods. Because each mode of transportation was the same across each disease type, it is valid to assume that there is an issue wrong with the data wrangling process. However, after much time attempting to examine and manipulate the data, I could not solve this issue and will attempt to work on this before the final project. Coronary heart disease did have the highest mean values, which makes sense due to general knowledge about common causes of death.Â 

modecor <- transhealth %>%
  group_by(modenew) %>%
  filter(coronary==1) %>%
    filter(modenew != "NA") %>%
  summarise(mean(`Age-Adjusted_Rate`),
            sd(`Age-Adjusted_Rate`))

Data visualizations

The scatter plots of all disease type age adjusted rates versus use of a car as a form of transportation showed very horizontal linear regression lines. The scatter plot of use of physical commuting versus disease type age adjusted rates did seem to show a minimally negative association between the pair (except for diabetes, which was very horizontal), which also makes sense given that this group had slightly lower standard deviations in disease rates. Lastly, the scatter plot of all disease types had minimal positive associations with diabetes and coronary heart age adjusted death rates (Alzheimer rates seemed to be very horizontal).

plots <- transhealth %>%
  filter(!is.na(modetransportpercent) & !is.na(coronaryrate) & !is.na(coronary) & modenew == "car")
plots %>% 
    ggplot(mapping = aes(x = coronaryrate, y = modetransportpercent)) +
  geom_point( position="jitter") + 
  geom_smooth(method = lm, se = FALSE, col = "black")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

For a broader scale investigation of health for each county, rankings were assessed by modes of transportation. From the graph, counties with greater use of cars seemed to have the highest rankings, then physical commuting, then at home work and public transportation tied with the lowest rankings.

plots <- transhealth %>%
  filter(!is.na(modenew) & !is.na(Rank_Order))
ggplot(plots, aes(x=modenew, y= Rank_Order)) +
     geom_bar(stat='identity') +
scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2")

In the final step of analysis, I wanted to test whether location had any impact on health indicators and could potentially influence the association between health indicators and types of transportation. In general, it seems that Orange, Riverside, and Imperial counties all have higher rankings than other counties in Southern California, of which could potentially interfere with investigations.

plots <- transhealth %>%
  filter(!is.na(modetransportpercent) & !is.na(County) & modenew=="car")
ggplot(plots, aes(x=County, y= modetransportpercent, fill= rankcat)) +
     geom_bar(stat='identity')
